ce:section.ce:para:
To investigate the effect of hydrothermal temperature on the lattice parameter, the average crystallite size was calculated using Debye Scherrer's law, as given in Eq. (2) [20]. As shown in Table 2 , the measured crystallite sizes of ZnO/NCQD 100, ZnO/NCQD 115, ZnO/NCQD 130, ZnO/NCQD 145, and ZnO/NCQD 160 were 5.42, 11.09, 8.63, 8.26, and 9.35 nm, respectively. The crystallite size increased with increasing hydrothermal temperature. A smaller crystallite size indicates a broad peak and low crystallinity. The FWHM of the (
101
) crystalline plane decreased with increasing hydrothermal temperature. However, the number of NCQD on the surface of ZnO might increase the FWHM owing to the lack of crystallinity [25].

The photocatalytic phenomena are affected by the generation and transfer of electrons and holes. This depends on the design of the photocatalyst material to enhance the electron transfer between the ZnO/NCQD and the dye molecule interface. Photocatalysis begun when the incident light, which had a higher energy than the energy band gap, irradiated ZnO/NCQD, and electrons (
e −
) from the valence band (VB) were excited to the conductance band (CB) and left a hole (
h +
) in the VB to generate photoexcited charge carriers of electron-hole pairs on the photocatalyst surface. The adsorbed NCQD on the surface of the ZnO particles were able to receive the photogenerated electrons, and those electrons were then capable of reacting with the adsorbed oxygen molecules (O2) to produce highly reactive oxygen radicals (O2 −*) [35]. Additionally, there were the holes that might interact with the H2O molecules that had been adsorbed to create hydroxyl radicals (OH*). The dye molecules' mineralization was caused by these highly reactive radicals. Due to the large capacity for electron storage provided by the carbon nanostructure, the presence of NCQD here not only enhanced charge carrier separation but also prevented charge carrier recombination [40]. Increasing the generation of charge carriers and hydroxyl radicals enhances photocatalytic activity [20]. The illustration of photocatalytics mechanism using ZnO/NCQD nanoflower is shown in Fig. 11 .
